{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584132","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584132"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:39:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:39:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14402"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14402"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.8,0.02,0.18,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7097"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113915"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7097"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14402"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95934"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4900"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"8411"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16935"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17128"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113915","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113915"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe internal surface of the heart\u0027s ventricles contains various muscular structures that contribute to cardiac function.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures represents the muscular ridges found on the internal surface of the heart\u0027s ventricles?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aortic vestibule","Trabeculae carneae","Septomarginal trabecula","Pectinate muscles","Chordae tendineae"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Etrabeculae carneae\u003C/strong\u003E. These are irregular muscular columns on the internal surface of the ventricles of the heart, particularly prominent in the right ventricle. These ridges help prevent the walls of the ventricles from sticking together and aid in the efficient pumping of blood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eaortic vestibule\u003C/strong\u003E is the smooth-walled portion of the left ventricle, just below the aortic valve. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eseptomarginal trabecula\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as the moderator band, is a muscular band in the right ventricle that carries part of the right bundle branch of the conduction system. \u003Cstrong\u003EPectinate muscles\u003C/strong\u003E are parallel ridges of cardiac muscle found in the walls of the right and left atria, not the ventricles. The \u003Cstrong\u003Echordae tendineae\u003C/strong\u003E are fibrous strings that connect the papillary muscles to the atrioventricular valves, preventing valve prolapse during ventricular contraction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Trabeculae carneae are irregular muscular columns on the internal surface of the ventricles of the heart.","Other internal cardiac structures include the septomarginal trabecula, pectinate muscles, and chordae tendineae, each with distinct locations and functions."],"references":["Netter, F. H. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: Classic Regional Approach-Ebook. 2022. Elsevier Health Sciences","Van Vleet, J. F., Ferrans, V. J., \u0026 Herman, E. Cardiovascular and skeletal muscle systems. Chapter 35 - Cardiovascular and Skeletal Muscle Systems. Handbook of toxicologic pathology, 539-624. 2022. 2nd edition. Academic Press."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95934"}},"question":{"data"